2025-12-12 | Minimum Cost to Split Array into 3 Subarrays

	Question
Given an integer array nums,  
divide it into exactly 3 contiguous non-empty subarrays and return the **minimum possible sum** of the costs of these subarrays.

	Approach
1.	Since subarrays must be contiguous and non-empty:
	-	Choose two split points i and j such that:
			0 < i < j < n
	-	The three subarrays will be:
			[0 .. i-1], [i .. j-1], [j .. n-1]
2.	The cost of this partition is:
			nums[0] + nums[i] + nums[j]
3.	nums[0] is fixed for all partitions.
4.	So the task reduces to:
	-	Choose indices i and j (i < j)
	-	Minimize nums[i] + nums[j]
5.	Optimized strategy:
	1.	Fix j as the start of the third subarray.
	2.	Keep track of the **minimum nums[i]** seen so far for i < j.
	3.	For each j from 2 to n-1:
			total = nums[0] + minPrefix + nums[j]
4.	Keep the minimum of all such totals.
5.	Time Complexity: O(n)  
   Space Complexity: O(1)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    int minimumCost(vector<int>& nums) {
        int n = nums.size();
        int ans = INT_MAX;

        int minPrefix = nums[1];

        for (int j = 2; j < n; j++) {
            ans = min(ans, nums[0] + minPrefix + nums[j]);
            minPrefix = min(minPrefix, nums[j]);
        }

        return ans;
    }
};
